\f2\i\fs28 \cf0 \strokec3 Dear Ir\'e8ne,\uc0\u8232 I got your letter of June 5 which arrived in Warsaw the 12th. I find that [delay] excessive... I arrived in Prague this morning and will leave tomorrow evening for Jachymow. I\'92m bewildered by the life I\'92m leading and incapable of telling you anything intelligent. I ask myself, what fundamental vice is there in the organization of humanity that makes this sort of agitation, to a certain degree, necessary? Mrs. Meloney [the American journalist who encouraged Marie to expose herself to the press] would call it, \'93Dignifying science.\'94 And what\'92s undeniable is the sincerity of everyone who does these things and their conviction that they are necessary.\u8232 Here I\'92m in a magnificent apartment, bedroom, sitting-room and bathroom, overlooking the river bordered by hills, and full of flowers they gave me at the train station\'97mostly roses since it\'92s their season. Unfortunately it\'92s gray, and I\'92m afraid it will rain.... With hugs,\u8232 M\'e9
